  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Abbreviation: HUS\nSimilar to\nTTP\n(which is more common in adults), but associated with less central nervous system and more renal involvement.\nMost cases occur in children <10yr (⅔ of cases in < 5yr)\n80-90% cases due to\nE. coli\nO157:H7 infection\nShiga toxin may induce autoantibody to CD36 (found on endothelial cells and platelets)\nMay also be caused by\nshigella\n,\nyersinia\n,\ncampylobacter\n,\nsalmonella",
      "subsections": {
        "Types": {
          "text": "Typical\nOccurs 2-14d after development of infectious\ndiarrhea\n(bloody, no fever)\nAtypical\nOccurs in older children and adults\nExtrarenal involvement is common (difficult to distinguish from\nTTP\n)\nMay be caused by atypical pathogens (\nEBV\n,\nS. pneumo\n) or immunosuppression",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
